<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="lesson5_3" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title> Quantum State Representation: Bra-Ket</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>Let's start our exploration of quantum state representations with bra-ket notation.</p>
  </introduction>

  <subsection
    xml:id="bra_ket_state" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Bra-Ket Quantum Representation</title>

    <p> The purpose of <term>bra-ket notation</term> is to express the probability of each potential
      outcome. Therefore, there are two parts to each <term>term</term>: the <em>outcome</em> and
      its <em>probability</em>.</p>

    <p> Bra-ket notation favors ease of calculation over easy readability of the probability,
      but it is easier to read than its alternative, vector notation.</p>

    <p> Each outcome is expressed in a <term>ket</term>, which you've already seen in this textbook: <m>\ket{0}
    </m>
      , <m>\ket{+}</m>, etc. Often, a general quantum state is described using the Greek letter psi: <m>\ket{\psi}
    </m>
      :</p>

    <md>
      <mrow> \ket{\psi} = a \ket{0} + b \ket{1} </mrow>
    </md>

    <sidebyside widths="50% 50%" valign="top">
      <p> In the figure to the right, we are expressing the probabilities of measuring apples or
        bananas. Each term in the expression represents a single outcome and are <em>added
          together</em>. The outcome (apple or banana) is placed inside of the ket, and the <term>probability
        amplitude</term> (rather than the probability) is placed just before the ket. </p>

      <image source="L5.3.braket.png" width="66%" />
    </sidebyside>

    <p> The relationship between probability amplitude and probability is:</p>

    <p>
      <md> <mrow> \text{probability} = |\text{probability amplitude}|^2 </mrow> </md>
    </p>

    <p> In this notation, if there is equal probability, or 1/2 probability of each of two outcomes,
      then the <em>probability amplitude</em> for each outcome will be <m>\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}</m>.</p>

    <!--
      <insert>picture like the one above with apples and bananas but with the terms 1/rt(2)
        for each</insert>
    </p>-->

    <exercise label="Bra-Ket_Heads_and_Tails">
      <title>Coin Flip in Bra-Ket Notation</title>
      <idx>bra-ket coin flip</idx>
      <statement>
        <p>If <m>H</m> is heads and <m>T</m> is tails, what is the probability of getting heads and
          tails for the following state?</p>
        <p>
          <md> <mrow> \frac{1}{\sqrt{3}} \ket{H} + \frac{\sqrt{2}}{\sqrt{3}} \ket{T} </mrow> </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <choices randomize="yes">
        <choice correct="yes">
          <statement>
            <p><m>\frac{1}{3}</m> chance of heads, <m>\frac{2}{3}</m> chance of tails</p>
          </statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>Yes! By squaring each probability amplitude, you get the probability of
              getting the corresponding outcome.</p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p><m>\frac{1}{\sqrt{3}}</m> chance of heads, <m>\frac{\sqrt{2}}{\sqrt{3}}</m> chance of tails</p>
          </statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>Remember that the bra-ket notation shows probability amplitudes, not probability.</p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p><m>\frac{2}{3}</m> chance of heads, <m>\frac{1}{3}</m> chance of tails</p>
          </statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>Make sure you associate the probability with the corresponding outcome.</p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p><m>\frac{1}{2}</m> chance of heads, <m>\frac{1}{2}</m> chance of tails</p>
          </statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>This is a special coin! Make sure you check probabilities from the bra-ket notation.</p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
      </choices>
      <hint>
        <p>Bra-ket notation uses probability amplitudes, which are squared to get probabilities.</p>
      </hint>
    </exercise>


    <p> We can see that this notation is very flexible to represent all kinds of probabilities. If
      we want to express outcomes from the raincoat/raining example from <xref
        ref="sec-independent-probabilities" />, it would look like the following:</p>

    <p>50% chance of sun, 50% chance of rain:</p>
    <md> <mrow> \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\ket{☀️} + \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}
      \ket{🌧️} </mrow> </md>

    <p>75% chance of no raincoat (👕), 25% chance of raincoat (🧥):</p>
    <md> <mrow> \sqrt{\frac{3}{4}} \ket{👕} + \sqrt{\frac{1}{4}} \ket{🧥}
      = \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \ket{👕} + \frac{1}{2} \ket{🧥}</mrow> </md>

    <p>Remember: to compute probability amplitudes for bra-ket notation, calculate the <em>square
      root</em> of the probability of each outcome.</p>

    <p> In quantum computing, the possible values for a quantum bit (qubit) are 0 or 1. So
      a qubit in a 50/50 superposition of 0 and 1 would have the state: </p>

    <md> <mrow> \ket{+} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \ket{0} + \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \ket{1} </mrow> </md>

    <p> If there is negative phase, then a negative sign will be placed in front of the <m>\ket{1}</m>
      state: </p>
    <md> <mrow> \ket{-} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \ket{0} - \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \ket{1} </mrow> </md>

    <p>This convention is in line with our convention of placing the negative sign on the black ball
      in visual representation!</p>

    <!--
      <insert>A few exercises - give a state and answer the probabilities,
        give the probabilities and answer the state. Through in phase into one of them.</insert>
    </p>-->

    <exercise label="Bra-Ket-Exercise-1">
      <title>Bra-Ket Notation Exercise 1</title>
      <idx>bra-ket notation exercise 1</idx>
      <statement>
        <p>Consider the following quantum state:</p>
        <p>
          <md> <mrow> \frac{1}{2} \ket{0} + \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \ket{1} </mrow> </md>
        </p>
        <p>What is the probability of measuring a 0?</p>
      </statement>
      <choices randomize="yes">
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\frac{1}{2}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
        <choice correct="yes">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\frac{1}{4}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
      </choices>
      <hint>
        <p>Bra-ket notation uses probability amplitudes, which are squared to get probabilities.</p>
      </hint>
    </exercise>

    <exercise label="Bra-Ket-Exercise-2">
      <title>Bra-Ket Notation Exercise 2</title>
      <idx>bra-ket notation exercise 2</idx>
      <introduction>
        <p>Bra-ket notation gives us a flexible notation for any sort of superposition state.
          Consider a weighted dice with the following probabilities of each outcome: <ul>
            <li>0% chance of <m>\ket{1}</m></li>
            <li>10% chance of <m>\ket{2}</m></li>
            <li>15% chance of <m>\ket{3}</m></li>
            <li>40% chance of <m>\ket{4}</m></li>
            <li>20% chance of <m>\ket{5}</m></li>
            <li>15% chance of <m>\ket{6}</m></li>
          </ul>
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>What would the coefficient of the <m>\ket{3}</m> term be?</p>
        </statement>
        <choices randomize="yes">
          <choice>
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m>\frac{1}{\sqrt{6}}</m>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </choice>
          <choice correct="yes">
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m>\frac{\sqrt{15}}{10}</m>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </choice>
          <choice>
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m>\frac{1}{\sqrt{15}}</m>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </choice>
          <choice>
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m>\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}</m>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </choice>
        </choices>
        <hint>
          <p>Bra-ket notation uses probability amplitudes, which are squared to get probabilities.</p>
        </hint>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>What would the coefficient of the <m>\ket{5}</m> term be?</p>
        </statement>
        <choices randomize="yes">
          <choice>
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m>\frac{1}{\sqrt{6}}</m>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </choice>
          <choice correct="yes">
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m>\frac{1}{\sqrt{5}}</m>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </choice>
          <choice>
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m>\frac{1}{\sqrt{20}}</m>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </choice>
          <choice>
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m>1</m>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </choice>
        </choices>
        <hint>
          <p>Bra-ket notation uses probability amplitudes, which are squared to get probabilities.</p>
        </hint>
      </task>
    </exercise>

    <exercise label="Bra-Ket-Exercise-3">
      <title>Bra-Ket Notation Exercise 3</title>
      <idx>bra-ket notation exercise 3</idx>
      <statement>
        <p>Consider the following quantum state:</p>
        <p>
          <image source="L4_3_2_E.png" width="20%" />
        </p>
        <p>What is the proper way to express this state in bra-ket notation?</p>
      </statement>
      <choices randomize="yes">
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>-\frac{1}{2}\ket{0} + \frac{1}{2} \ket{1}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\frac{1}{2}\ket{0} - \frac{1}{2} \ket{1}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
        <choice correct="yes">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\ket{0} - \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \ket{1}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\ket{0} + \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \ket{1}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>- \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\ket{0} - \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \ket{1}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
      </choices>
    </exercise>

  </subsection>

  <subsection
    xml:id="multi-qubit-bra_ket" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Multi-Qubit Bra-Ket Notation</title>

    <p> Now that we've seen how to represent a single qubit state in bra-ket notation, the natural
      next question is: "How do we represent a two-qubit state?" Luckily for us, bra-ket notation's
      flexibility comes in handy here. We know that an individual qubit only has two possible
      outcomes: 0 or 1. For a pair of qubits, however, we have
      each combination of possible outcomes: 00, 01, 10, 11. Thus, the general bra-ket notation for
      a 2-qubit state looks like:</p>

    <md> <mrow> \ket{\psi} = a \ket{00} + b \ket{01} + c \ket{10} + d \ket{11} </mrow> </md>

    <p>Looking at the state above, we can see that <m>a</m> is the probability amplitude for the
      outcome <m>00</m>, meaning there is a <m>a^2</m> chance of measuring <m>00</m>. This applies to <m>b</m>
      , <m>c</m>, and <m>d</m>.</p>

    <p> We can also combine two independent qubits into a 2-qubit bra-ket notation, just like we
      represented two qubits using our visual representation (<xref ref="sec-two-qubit-visual" />).
      In our notation, we call this operation a <term>tensor product</term> of the two qubits, using
      the symbol <m>\otimes</m>. For basis states, we simply combine the two basis states into a single
      ket, as we have already seen: </p>

    <md> <mrow> \ket{0} \otimes \ket{1} = \ket{01} </mrow> </md>

    <p> The tricky part is calculating the probability of the combined values from the single qubit
      probabilities when the individual qubits are in superposition. This is when our independent
      probability calculations come into play <mdash /> you just multiply the appropriate values
      together. </p>

    <p>
      <image source="L5.3.1to2qubitsbraket.png" width="60%" />
    </p>

    <p>This might look familiar: combining independent qubits is analogous to distribution when
      multiplying two additive terms in algebra! Notice how similar the two expansions below look:</p>

    <md>
      <mrow>(a\ket{0} + b\ket{1}) \otimes (c\ket{0} + d\ket{1}) \amp= ac\ket{00} + ad\ket{01} + bc\ket{10} +
        bd\ket{11}</mrow>
      <mrow>(ax + by) (cx + dy) \amp= ac(x^2) + ad(xy) + bc(yx) + bd(y^2)</mrow>
    </md>

    <p>You can also factor out combined qubit states, using the same algebra rules!
    </p>
    <md> <mrow> \ket{00} + \ket{01} = \ket{0} \otimes (\ket{0} + \ket{1}) </mrow> </md>
    <p>However, the order of the individual qubits is highly important, because the order
      corresponds to each individual qubit in our system. Thus, multiplied terms <em>cannot</em> be
      reordered as in algebraic expressions.</p>
    <md> <mrow> \ket{0} \otimes (\ket{0} + \ket{1}) \ne (\ket{0} + \ket{1}) \otimes \ket{0} </mrow> </md>
    <p>It's important to note that not all multi-qubit states can be factored out into individual
      qubits, e.g. <m>\ket{00} + \ket{11}</m>. These states have fascinating implications in quantum computing, but
      we'll dig deeper into these states at a later time.</p>

    <exercise label="Bra-Ket-Multiple-Qubits-1">
      <title>Bra-ket Notation with Multiple Qubits Exercise 1</title>
      <idx>bra-ket notation with multiple qubits exercise 1</idx>
      <statement>
        <p>Convert the two independent qubits into 2-qubit bra-ket notation:</p>
        <p>Qubit 1: <m>\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \ket{0} + \frac{1}{2} \ket{1}</m>. Qubit 2: <m>1 \ket{0} + 0 \ket{1} </m></p>
      </statement>
      <choices randomize="yes">
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \ket{00} + 0 \ket{01} + \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \ket{10} + 1\ket{11}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\frac{1}{2} \ket{00} + \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \ket{01} + 0 \ket{10} + 0 \ket{11}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
        <choice correct="yes">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \ket{00} + 0 \ket{01} + \frac{1}{2} \ket{10} + 0\ket{11}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\frac{1}{2} \ket{00} + 0 \ket{01} + \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \ket{10} + 0\ket{11}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
      </choices>
      <hint>
        <p>
          Follow the same rules you follow to multiply algebraic expressions!
        </p>
      </hint>
    </exercise>

    <exercise label="Bra-Ket-Multiple-Qubits-2">
      <title>Bra-ket Notation with Multiple Qubits Exercise 2</title>
      <idx>bra-ket notation with multiple qubits exercise 2</idx>
      <statement>
        <p>Convert the two independent qubits into 2-qubit bra-ket notation:</p>
        <p>Qubit 1: <m>\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \ket{0} + \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \ket{1}</m>. Qubit 2: <m>\ket{0}</m></p>
      </statement>
      <choices randomize="yes">
        <choice correct="yes">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \ket{00} + 0 \ket{01} + \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \ket{10} + 0\ket{11}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>0 \ket{00} + \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \ket{01} + \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \ket{10} + 0 \ket{11}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>0 \ket{00} + \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \ket{01} + 0 \ket{10} + \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \ket{11}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \ket{00} + 0 \ket{01} + \ket{10} + \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \ket{11}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
      </choices>
      <hint>
        <p>
          Follow the same rules you follow to multiply algebraic expressions!
        </p>
      </hint>
    </exercise>

    <note>
      <title>A note on phase</title>
      <p> In 1-qubit notation, we introduced the idea of <em>positive</em> and <em>negative</em>
        phase, which we represented (by convention) with the sign on the <m>\ket{1}</m> term in the
        expression. However, in 2-qubit (and higher), we have more than two terms. Thus, when we say
        that a multi-qubit state has negative phase, we also need to be precise about <em>which term
        the negative sign
          is on</em> <mdash /> different placements of the negative sign results in different quantum
        states. These two states are <em>not equivalent</em>:</p>

      <md>
        <mrow>\frac{1}{2} \ket{00} - \frac{1}{2} \ket{01} + \frac{1}{2} \ket{10} +\frac{1}{2} \ket{11}</mrow>
        <mrow>\frac{1}{2} \ket{00} + \frac{1}{2} \ket{01} - \frac{1}{2} \ket{10} +\frac{1}{2} \ket{11}</mrow>
      </md>

      <p>We'll explore phase and equivalent states further in a future chapter.</p>
    </note>
  </subsection>

  <subsection
    xml:id="bra_ket_state_simplification" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Bra-Ket State Simplification</title>

    <p>Just like with fractions, there are multiple ways of expressing the same state. Every time a
      state is calculated, we then simplify the state into its preferred form. We saw some similar
      simplification rules for our visual representation in <xref
        ref="sec-simplify-superposition-visual" />. Let's learn a few simplification rules for
      bra-ket notation!</p>

    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>The order of the outcomes is always in increasing numeric order
          (starting with all 0's and ending with all 1's). Below is a properly formed
          3-qubit state: </p>
        <md> <mrow> a\ket{000} + b\ket{001} + c\ket{010} + d\ket{011} + e\ket{100} + f\ket{101} + g\ket{110}
          + h\ket{111} </mrow> </md>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>You may omit any term whose probability is 0. </p>
        <md> <mrow> \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\ket{00} + 0\ket{01} + 0\ket{10} + \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\ket{11} =
          \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\ket{00} + \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\ket{11} </mrow> </md>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>The first term in the state (the <term>leading term</term>) is never in negative phase.
          If the leading term is negative, you can multiply the whole state by <m>-1</m> and obtain an
          equivalent state (as we have seen previously in <xref
            ref="sec-simplify-superposition-visual" />).</p>
        <md>
          <mrow>\amp-\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\ket{00} + \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\ket{01} -
            \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\ket{10} +
            \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\ket{11}</mrow>
          <mrow>= \amp\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\ket{00} - \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\ket{01} +
            \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\ket{10} -
            \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\ket{11}</mrow>
        </md>
      </li>
    </ol>

    <p> One rule that is different from algebraic expressions is that you can multiply all terms by
      the same number and the resulting state is the same; the <em>comparison</em> of the states is
      what matters, not the absolute values. However, the purpose of bra-ket notation is to be
      easily able to tell by looking at it what the probabilities of each outcome are (and still be
      able to perform operations). Therefore, we prefer to keep bra-ket states <term>
        normalized</term>.</p>

    <p> To normalize a bra-ket state, we want to ensure that the coefficients of each term represent
      probability amplitudes. In order to do so, the sum of the squares of each coefficient should
      add up to 1. This represents the fact that there is a 100% chance of getting any of the
      outcomes expressed in the state. For example, for a single qubit of the form <m>a\ket{0} + b\ket{1}</m>, <m>a^2 + b^2 = 1</m>.</p>

    <exercise label="Bra-Ket-Notation-Valid-States">
      <title>Bra-Ket Notation: Normalized States</title>
      <idx>bra-ket notation: normalized states</idx>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Which of the following states are written in valid, normalized bra-ket notation?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <choices randomize="yes">
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\ket{0} + \ket{1}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
        <choice correct="yes">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\ket{1010}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\frac{1}{10} \ket{0} + \frac{9}{10} \ket{1}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
        <choice correct="yes">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\frac{1}{10} \ket{0} + \frac{\sqrt{99}}{10} \ket{1}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
      </choices>
    </exercise>

    <note>
      <p>If all outcomes are the same probability some people omit the leading term.
        However, none of the answers in this book use this rule because it hides the true
        probability.</p>
    </note>

    <exercise label="Bra-Ket-Simplification">
      <title>Bra-ket Notation Simplification</title>
      <idx>bra-ket notation simplification</idx>
      <statement>
        <p>Simplify the following bra-ket notation into the conventional form:</p>
        <p>
          <md> <mrow> -\frac{1}{\sqrt{7}} \ket{00} + 0 \ket{10} + \frac{2}{\sqrt{7}} \ket{11} - \frac{\sqrt{2}}{\sqrt{7}} \ket{01} </mrow> </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <choices randomize="yes">
        <choice correct="yes">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\frac{1}{\sqrt{7}} \ket{00} + \frac{\sqrt{2}}{\sqrt{7}} \ket{01} - \frac{2}{\sqrt{7}} \ket{11}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>- \frac{1}{\sqrt{7}} \ket{00} - \frac{\sqrt{2}}{\sqrt{7}} \ket{01} + \frac{2}{\sqrt{7}} \ket{11}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\frac{1}{\sqrt{7}} \ket{00} + \frac{\sqrt{2}}{\sqrt{7}} \ket{01} + 0 \ket{10} - \frac{2}{\sqrt{7}} \ket{11}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\frac{1}{\sqrt{7}} \ket{00} - \frac{2}{\sqrt{7}} \ket{11} + \frac{\sqrt{2}}{\sqrt{7}} \ket{01}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
      </choices>
      <hint>
        <p>
          Follow the same rules you follow to multiply algebraic expressions!
        </p>
      </hint>
    </exercise>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="bra_ket_gate_operation" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Calculating Quantum Gate Results</title>
    <p>Now that we have a way to represent quantum states, the natural next question is: how do we
      perform operations on these states? Bra-ket notation is handy to perform simple operations.
    </p>

    <p>When we first started looking at gates, we thought of them as operating on 0 and 1. Now,
      however, with our improved understanding of qubits in superposition, we can think about how
      gates act on a <em>general</em> quantum state. The general rule for applying a gate to a
      quantum state is to <em>apply its effects to the
        appropriate qubit in each term of the bra-ket state</em>. This is the beauty of this
      notation! </p>

    <p>Let's start with the first gate we learned, acting on a general single-qubit state <m>a_0 \ket{0} + a_1 \ket{1}</m>:</p>

    <paragraphs>
      <title><c>NOT</c> Gate </title>
      <p>The <c>NOT</c> gate changes <m>\ket{0}</m> to <m>\ket{1}</m>, and <m>\ket{1}</m> to <m>\ket{0}</m>.</p>
      <md>
        <mrow>a_0 \ket{0} + a_1 \ket{1} \amp \xrightarrow{\text{NOT}} a_0 \ket{1} + a_1 \ket{0}</mrow>
        <mrow> \amp = a_1 \ket{0} + a_0 \ket{1} </mrow>
      </md>
    </paragraphs>

    <p>After we apply the gate to each term in the state, we <em>reorganize the terms</em> so that
      they are in the right order according to our convention.</p>

    <image source="GeneralNOT2.png" width="40%" />

    <p>What about the <c>H</c> gate? We apply our knowledge of how the <c>H</c> gate acts on the basis
      states, <m>\ket{0}</m> and <m>\ket{1}</m>:</p>

    <paragraphs>
      <title><c>H</c> Gate </title>
      <p>The <c>H</c> gate changes <m>\ket{0}</m> to a 50/50 superposition with positive phase, and <m>\ket{1}</m>
        to a 50/50 superposition with negative phase.</p>
      <md>
        <mrow>a_0 \ket{0} + a_1 \ket{1} \amp \xrightarrow{\text{H}} a_0 \Big( \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \ket{0} + \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \ket{1} \Big) + a_1 \Big( \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \ket{0} - \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \ket{1} \Big)</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} (a_0 + a_1) \ket{0} + \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} (a_0 - a_1) \ket{1}  </mrow>
      </md>
    </paragraphs>

    <p>How does this look on a specific state?</p>

    <example>
      <title>Applying the <c>H</c> gate to the <m>\ket{+}</m> state</title>
      <p> From our earlier discussions, we know that the output of this operation is <m>\ket{0}</m>. Let's
        use our brand-new mathematical model to verify this behavior! </p>

      <p>
        Let's first remind ourselves how the equal superposition state with positive phase is
        represented in bra-ket notation:</p>

      <md> <mrow> \ket{+} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \ket{0} + \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \ket{1} </mrow> </md>

      <p>Now, let's apply the <c>H</c> gate to each of the terms in the expression:</p>

      <md>
      <mrow>\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \ket{0} + \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \ket{1} \amp\xrightarrow{\text{H}}
        \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \Big(\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \ket{0} + \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \ket{1}\Big) +
        \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \Big(\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \ket{0} - \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \ket{1}\Big) </mrow>
      <mrow>\amp= \frac{1}{2} \ket{0} + \frac{1}{2} \ket{1} + \frac{1}{2} \ket{0} - \frac{1}{2}
        \ket{1} </mrow>
      <mrow>\amp= \ket{0}</mrow>
    </md>

      <p>Voila!</p>
    </example>

    <exercise label="Bra-Ket-Single-Qubit-Gates-1">
      <title>Bra-Ket Notation: Applying Single-Qubit Gates 1</title>
      <idx>bra-ket notation: applying single-qubit gates 1</idx>
      <statement>
        <p>The <c>NOT</c> operator is applied to the initial vector: <m>\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \ket{0} + \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \ket{1}</m>. What will the result be
          in bra-ket notation?</p>
      </statement>
      <choices randomize="yes">
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \ket{0} + \frac{1}{2} \ket{1}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\frac{1}{2} \ket{0} + \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \ket{1}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
        <choice correct="yes">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \ket{0} + \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \ket{1}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>Correct! While the <c>NOT</c> operator switches the probabilities of the <m>\ket{0}</m> and <m>\ket{1}</m>
              terms, since they are equal, there is no overall effect.</p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Cannot be determined
            </p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
      </choices>
    </exercise>

    <exercise label="Bra-Ket-Single-Qubit-Gates-2">
      <title>Bra-Ket Notation: Applying Single-Qubit Gates 2</title>
      <idx>bra-ket notation: applying single-qubit gates 2</idx>
      <statement>
        <p>Let's discover the behavior of the <c>Z</c> gate together. Suppose our initial state is <m>a \ket{0} + b \ket{1}</m>.
          What is the result of applying a <c>Z</c> gate to this state? </p>
      </statement>
      <choices randomize="yes">
        <choice correct="yes">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>a \ket{0} - b \ket{1}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>a \ket{0} + b \ket{1}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>b \ket{0} - a \ket{1}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>- a \ket{0} - b \ket{1}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
      </choices>
    </exercise>

    <p>What about two-qubit gates, like <c>SWAP</c> or <c>CNOT</c>?</p>

    <paragraphs>
      <title><c>SWAP</c> Gate</title>
      <p> For the <c>SWAP</c> gate, swap the values of the two qubits that are being swapped. This looks
        like <m>\ket{xy} \xrightarrow{\text{SWAP}(1,2)} \ket{yx}</m>. Here, the <m>(1, 2)</m> indicates that we are swapping the first and second qubits
        in our state (this will prove useful when your state has more than 2 qubits).</p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs>
      <title><c>CNOT</c> Gate</title>
      <p>The <c>CNOT</c> gate is a little tricky. When applying the gate, we need to keep track of which
        qubit is the <term>control</term>, and which qubit is the <term>target</term>. The general
        convention to indicate which is which is with an arrow:</p>
      <md> <mrow> \text{CNOT}(\text{control} \rightarrow \text{target}) </mrow> </md>
      <p>If the <em>
          control</em> for a given term is 1, then we flip the <em>target</em> qubit in that term.
        Otherwise, the term does not change. For example, if we are applying a <c>CNOT</c> gate where
        the first qubit is the control and the second qubit is the target:</p>
      <md> <mrow> \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\ket{00} + \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\ket{11}
        \xrightarrow{\text{CNOT}(1 \rightarrow 2)}
        \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\ket{00} + \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\ket{10} </mrow> </md>

      <p>In the first term, the control is 0, so this term does not change. In the second term, the
        control is 1, so we flip the second qubit in the term.</p>

      <p>Once again, after applying your gates, don't forget to <em>reorganize the terms</em> so
        that they are in the right order according to our convention!</p>
    </paragraphs>

    <exercise label="Bra-Ket-Two-Qubit-Gates">
      <title>Bra-Ket Notation: Applying Two-Qubit Gates</title>
      <idx>Bra-Ket Notation: Applying Two-Qubit Gates</idx>
      <statement>
        <p>The <c>SWAP</c> operator is applied to the initial vector: <m>a_0 \ket{00} + a_1 \ket{01}+ a_2 \ket{10}+ a_3 \ket{11}</m>. What will the result be
          in bra-ket notation?</p>
      </statement>
      <choices randomize="yes">
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>a_0 \ket{00} + a_1 \ket{01}+ a_2 \ket{10}+ a_3 \ket{11}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>a_3 \ket{00} + a_2 \ket{01}+ a_1 \ket{10}+ a_0 \ket{11}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
        <choice correct="yes">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>a_0 \ket{00} + a_2 \ket{01}+ a_1 \ket{10}+ a_3 \ket{11}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>a_1 \ket{00} + a_0 \ket{01}+ a_3 \ket{10}+ a_2 \ket{11}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
      </choices>
      <hint>
        <p>First apply the <c>SWAP</c> gate as we saw above. Then, reorganize the terms based on our
          conventional order.</p>
      </hint>
    </exercise>

    <p>While bra-ket notation is handy to keep track of probabilities and calculate simple gates,
      it starts becoming more and more unwieldy with more gates and more complex states. Is there
      perhaps another mathematical model we can use to help us out?</p>
  </subsection>
</section>
